  "What is bioaccumulation?": "",
  "The excessive growth and proliferation of algae populations in nutrient-enriched freshwater ponds": "",
  "The rapid reproduction and colony expansion of bacteria in warm, nutrient-rich environments": "",
  "The gradual accumulation and deposition of sediment particles along river channels and floodplains": "",
  "The gradual buildup of a toxic substance in an organism's tissues over its lifetime because the substance is absorbed faster than it is eliminated": "",
  "Bioaccumulation occurs when a substance (like mercury or DDT) is absorbed by an organism faster than it can be metabolized or excreted, causing concentrations to build up in tissues over time.": "",
  "What is biomagnification?": "",
  "The increasing concentration of a toxic substance at each successive trophic level in a food chain": "",
  "Using a microscope to view tiny organisms": "",
  "Magnifying the size of biological samples": "",
  "The growth of organisms to large sizes": "",
  "Biomagnification is the process by which the concentration of a persistent toxin increases at each trophic level of a food chain, meaning top predators accumulate the highest concentrations.": "",
  "What is a Superfund site?": "",
  "A national park that receives special federal funding for wildlife conservation and visitor programs": "",
  "A renewable energy facility such as a wind farm or solar installation built on reclaimed land": "",
  "A government savings account specifically allocated to finance future environmental restoration projects": "",
  "A contaminated location in the US designated for cleanup under the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA)": "",
  "Superfund sites are contaminated locations designated by the EPA for long-term cleanup under CERCLA, enacted in 1980 in response to Love Canal and similar toxic waste disasters.": "",
  "What is an environmental impact assessment (EIA)?": "",
