  "A layer of pure oxygen gas found at ground level that is produced by photosynthetic plant activity": "",
  "The ozone layer is a region in the stratosphere (15-35 km altitude) containing relatively high concentrations of ozone (O3) that absorbs 97-99% of the sun's harmful ultraviolet radiation.": "",
  "What is a point source of pollution?": "",
  "Any pollution found in a single point on a map": "",
  "Pollution from many diffuse sources": "",
  "Pollution that comes from a single, identifiable source such as a factory pipe or sewage outfall": "",
  "Pollution that only affects one species": "",
  "Point source pollution originates from a single, identifiable location such as a discharge pipe, smokestack, or oil well. It is generally easier to monitor and regulate than nonpoint source pollution.": "",
  "What is a nonpoint source of pollution?": "",
  "Pollution that exclusively occurs in ocean environments from ship discharges and offshore drilling platforms": "",
  "Pollution discharged directly from a factory's identifiable pipe or smokestack into the surrounding environment": "",
  "Pollution that is invisible to the naked eye and can only be detected using specialized laboratory instruments": "",
  "Pollution that comes from many diffuse sources over a wide area, such as agricultural runoff or urban stormwater": "",
  "Nonpoint source pollution comes from many scattered or diffuse sources, such as fertilizer runoff from farms, urban stormwater, and atmospheric deposition. It is harder to control than point source pollution.": "",
  "What is remediation in environmental science?": "",
  "The process of creating new pollutants": "",
  "The process of cleaning up and restoring a contaminated site to a safe condition": "",
  "A type of meditation practiced outdoors": "",
  "A remedy for common colds": "",
  "Environmental remediation is the process of removing pollutants or contaminants from soil, groundwater, or surface water to protect human health and restore ecosystem function at contaminated sites.": "",
  "What is an indicator species?": "",
