  "A regulation about animal testing in laboratories": "",
  "The Endangered Species Act of 1973 is one of the most powerful US conservation laws, providing legal protection for species at risk of extinction and the habitats they need to survive.": "",
  "In the 1950s, residents of Minamata, Japan began suffering from a mysterious neurological disease. Investigators discovered that a chemical factory was dumping mercury into the bay, which bioaccumulated in fish that residents ate daily. This case study illustrates:": "",
  "How industrial pollution can bioaccumulate through food chains, causing severe human health effects even far from the pollution source": "",
  "That neurological diseases are always caused by genetic factors inherited from previous generations": "",
  "That mercury is a harmless element commonly found in natural waterways and poses no health risks": "",
  "That eating fish from any water source is always inherently dangerous regardless of water quality": "",
  "The Minamata disease case demonstrates how mercury pollution bioaccumulates through aquatic food chains, reaching toxic concentrations in fish consumed by humans, causing devastating neurological damage.": "",
  "The recovery of the bald eagle population after the DDT ban shows that:": "",
  "Bald eagles genetically adapted to tolerate high concentrations of DDT in their body tissues": "",
  "Environmental regulations consistently fail to produce any meaningful recovery in wildlife populations": "",
  "Ecosystems that have experienced significant pollution damage cannot ever recover their original species": "",
  "Effective environmental regulation can allow damaged populations to recover when the source of harm is eliminated": "",
  "After DDT was banned in 1972, bald eagle populations recovered from near-extinction to over 300,000 birds, proving that science-based regulation can successfully reverse environmental damage.": "",
  "A community near an old industrial site notices higher-than-average cancer rates. Environmental scientists test the soil and groundwater, finding toxic chemicals that match the factory's former products. The affected community is predominantly low-income and minority. This situation raises concerns about:": "",
