  "After the 1969 Cuyahoga River fire, public outcry led to the creation of the EPA and passage of the Clean Water Act. A city today has a river with similarly high industrial pollution levels. Based on this case study, the most effective approach would be:": "",
  "Ignoring the pollution because rivers eventually clean themselves": "",
  "Covering the river with a lid": "",
  "Enforcing pollution regulations, identifying and stopping illegal discharges, and implementing cleanup efforts": "",
  "Moving the city to a different location": "",
  "The Cuyahoga River case study shows that strict regulation and enforcement can transform even severely polluted waterways. The Cuyahoga is now vastly cleaner due to Clean Water Act enforcement.": "",
